---
import Layout from '../../../layouts/Layout.astro';
---
<Layout title="How GNSS Works">
  <section class="section">
    <div class="container learn-container">

      <!-- Breadcrumb -->
      <nav class="breadcrumb">
        <a href="/learn">Learn</a>
        <span>›</span>
        <a href="/learn/fundamentals">Fundamentals</a>
        <span>›</span>
        <span>How GNSS Works</span>
      </nav>

      <div class="article-header">
        <span class="badge">Fundamentals · Article 1 of 5</span>
        <h1>How GNSS Works</h1>
        <p class="lead">
          Your phone knows where you are within a few metres, anywhere on Earth, using signals from
          satellites 20,000 km away. This article explains the physics and mathematics that make that possible —
          from atomic clocks in orbit to the position fix in your receiver.
        </p>
        <div class="article-meta">
          <span>12 min read</span>
          <span>·</span>
          <span>Last updated March 2026</span>
        </div>
      </div>

      <!-- TABLE OF CONTENTS -->
      <div class="toc">
        <div class="toc-title">Contents</div>
        <ol>
          <li><a href="#overview">The big picture</a></li>
          <li><a href="#ranging">Ranging — measuring distance with time</a></li>
          <li><a href="#trilateration">Trilateration — turning distances into a position</a></li>
          <li><a href="#four-satellites">Why four satellites?</a></li>
          <li><a href="#receiver">What the receiver actually does</a></li>
          <li><a href="#summary">Summary</a></li>
          <li><a href="#references">References</a></li>
        </ol>
      </div>

      <!-- SECTION 1 -->
      <h2 id="overview">The big picture</h2>
      <p>
        GNSS stands for <strong>Global Navigation Satellite System</strong> — the umbrella term for any
        satellite-based positioning system. GPS (USA), Galileo (EU), GLONASS (Russia) and BeiDou (China)
        are all GNSS constellations. They all work on the same fundamental principle.
      </p>
      <p>
        The core idea is simple: if you know exactly how far you are from several known points in space,
        you can calculate your own position. GNSS satellites are those known points. Your receiver measures
        the distance to each visible satellite and uses those distances to solve for its own location.
      </p>
      <p>
        The difficult part is <em>measuring distance to a satellite 20,200 km away with sub-metre accuracy</em>.
        GNSS does this by measuring time — specifically, how long a radio signal takes to travel from satellite to receiver.
      </p>

      <div class="callout callout-info">
        <div class="callout-icon">📐</div>
        <div>
          <strong>Key principle:</strong> Radio signals travel at the speed of light — approximately
          299,792,458 m/s in vacuum. If a signal takes 67 milliseconds to arrive, the satellite is
          approximately 0.067 × 299,792,458 ≈ <strong>20,095 km</strong> away.
        </div>
      </div>

      <!-- SECTION 2 -->
      <h2 id="ranging">Ranging — measuring distance with time</h2>
      <p>
        Each GNSS satellite continuously broadcasts a signal that contains two things:
      </p>
      <ul>
        <li>A <strong>ranging code</strong> — a precisely timed pattern of ones and zeros</li>
        <li>A <strong>navigation message</strong> — the satellite's position and clock information</li>
      </ul>
      <p>
        The receiver generates an identical copy of the ranging code internally. It then slides its copy
        in time until it aligns with the received signal. The time shift required for alignment is the
        signal travel time — called the <strong>propagation delay</strong>.
      </p>

      <div class="formula-block">
        <div class="formula">distance = c × Δt</div>
        <div class="formula-desc">
          where <em>c</em> = speed of light (299,792,458 m/s) and <em>Δt</em> = measured propagation delay (seconds)
        </div>
      </div>

      <p>
        This measured distance is called a <strong>pseudorange</strong> — "pseudo" because it contains errors,
        most importantly a timing error in the receiver's own clock.
      </p>

      <div class="callout callout-warn">
        <div class="callout-icon">⚠️</div>
        <div>
          <strong>Clock problem:</strong> A timing error of just 1 microsecond (0.000001 seconds) causes
          a ranging error of 300 metres. GNSS satellites carry atomic clocks accurate to nanoseconds,
          but receivers use much cheaper oscillators. This is why clock error must be solved for
          simultaneously with position — it is the fourth unknown.
        </div>
      </div>

      <!-- Pseudorange diagram -->
      <div class="diagram-wrap">
        <div class="diagram-label">Signal travel from satellite to receiver</div>
        <svg viewBox="0 0 680 180" width="100%" xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2000/svg">
          <defs>
            <marker id="arr" viewBox="0 0 10 10" refX="8" refY="5" markerWidth="6" markerHeight="6" orient="auto-start-reverse">
              <path d="M2 1L8 5L2 9" fill="none" stroke="context-stroke" stroke-width="1.5" stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round"/>
            </marker>
          </defs>
          <!-- Satellite -->
          <g>
            <rect x="40" y="30" width="100" height="44" rx="8" fill="none" stroke="var(--accent)" stroke-width="1"/>
            <text x="90" y="49" text-anchor="middle" font-size="12" fill="var(--accent)" font-family="var(--sans)" font-weight="500">Satellite</text>
            <text x="90" y="65" text-anchor="middle" font-size="11" fill="var(--text2)" font-family="var(--sans)">Atomic clock</text>
          </g>
          <!-- Receiver -->
          <g>
            <rect x="540" y="30" width="100" height="44" rx="8" fill="none" stroke="var(--accent2)" stroke-width="1"/>
            <text x="590" y="49" text-anchor="middle" font-size="12" fill="var(--accent2)" font-family="var(--sans)" font-weight="500">Receiver</text>
            <text x="590" y="65" text-anchor="middle" font-size="11" fill="var(--text2)" font-family="var(--sans)">Quartz clock</text>
          </g>
          <!-- Signal arrow -->
          <line x1="142" y1="52" x2="538" y2="52" stroke="var(--accent)" stroke-width="1.5" marker-end="url(#arr)" stroke-dasharray="6 4"/>
          <!-- Time labels -->
          <text x="90" y="110" text-anchor="middle" font-size="11" fill="var(--text3)" font-family="var(--mono)">t_transmit</text>
          <text x="590" y="110" text-anchor="middle" font-size="11" fill="var(--text3)" font-family="var(--mono)">t_receive</text>
          <!-- Delta t brace -->
          <line x1="140" y1="120" x2="540" y2="120" stroke="var(--text3)" stroke-width="0.5"/>
          <line x1="140" y1="115" x2="140" y2="125" stroke="var(--text3)" stroke-width="0.5"/>
          <line x1="540" y1="115" x2="540" y2="125" stroke="var(--text3)" stroke-width="0.5"/>
          <text x="340" y="142" text-anchor="middle" font-size="12" fill="var(--text2)" font-family="var(--mono)">Δt = t_receive − t_transmit</text>
          <text x="340" y="162" text-anchor="middle" font-size="11" fill="var(--text3)" font-family="var(--sans)">pseudorange ρ = c × Δt</text>
        </svg>
      </div>

      <!-- SECTION 3 -->
      <h2 id="trilateration">Trilateration — turning distances into a position</h2>
      <p>
        Once you have a distance to a satellite, you know you are somewhere on a <strong>sphere</strong>
        of that radius centred on the satellite. With distances from <em>three</em> satellites, you get
        three spheres — and you are at one of the (usually two) points where all three spheres intersect.
        In practice, one of those two points is deep inside the Earth and can be discarded, leaving
        a unique surface position. This geometric technique is called <strong>trilateration</strong>.
      </p>

      <div class="callout callout-info">
        <div class="callout-icon">💡</div>
        <div>
          <strong>Trilateration vs triangulation:</strong> These are often confused.
          Triangulation uses <em>angles</em> (as in surveying with a theodolite).
          Trilateration uses <em>distances</em>. GNSS is trilateration.
        </div>
      </div>

      <!-- Trilateration diagram -->
      <div class="diagram-wrap">
        <div class="diagram-label">Trilateration — intersection of spheres</div>
        <svg viewBox="0 0 680 300" width="100%" xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2000/svg">
          <defs>
            <marker id="arr2" viewBox="0 0 10 10" refX="8" refY="5" markerWidth="6" markerHeight="6" orient="auto-start-reverse">
              <path d="M2 1L8 5L2 9" fill="none" stroke="context-stroke" stroke-width="1.5" stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round"/>
            </marker>
          </defs>
          <!-- Sat 1 circle -->
          <circle cx="200" cy="100" r="130" fill="none" stroke="var(--accent)" stroke-width="1" opacity="0.4" stroke-dasharray="5 3"/>
          <!-- Sat 2 circle -->
          <circle cx="400" cy="80" r="150" fill="none" stroke="var(--accent2)" stroke-width="1" opacity="0.4" stroke-dasharray="5 3"/>
          <!-- Sat 3 circle -->
          <circle cx="300" cy="240" r="120" fill="none" stroke="#fbbf24" stroke-width="1" opacity="0.4" stroke-dasharray="5 3"/>
          <!-- Satellites -->
          <circle cx="200" cy="100" r="8" fill="var(--accent)" opacity="0.8"/>
          <text x="200" y="88" text-anchor="middle" font-size="11" fill="var(--accent)" font-family="var(--sans)">SV1</text>
          <circle cx="400" cy="80" r="8" fill="var(--accent2)" opacity="0.8"/>
          <text x="400" y="68" text-anchor="middle" font-size="11" fill="var(--accent2)" font-family="var(--sans)">SV2</text>
          <circle cx="300" cy="240" r="8" fill="#fbbf24" opacity="0.8"/>
          <text x="300" y="260" text-anchor="middle" font-size="11" fill="#fbbf24" font-family="var(--sans)">SV3</text>
          <!-- Intersection point (approximate) -->
          <circle cx="318" cy="150" r="10" fill="var(--text)" opacity="0.9"/>
          <circle cx="318" cy="150" r="5" fill="var(--accent)" opacity="1"/>
          <text x="340" y="146" font-size="12" fill="var(--text)" font-family="var(--sans)" font-weight="500">Your position</text>
          <!-- Range lines -->
          <line x1="208" y1="104" x2="312" y2="146" stroke="var(--accent)" stroke-width="0.8" stroke-dasharray="3 3" opacity="0.6" marker-end="url(#arr2)"/>
          <line x1="392" y1="86" x2="326" y2="146" stroke="var(--accent2)" stroke-width="0.8" stroke-dasharray="3 3" opacity="0.6" marker-end="url(#arr2)"/>
          <line x1="302" y1="232" x2="316" y2="160" stroke="#fbbf24" stroke-width="0.8" stroke-dasharray="3 3" opacity="0.6" marker-end="url(#arr2)"/>
          <!-- Range labels -->
          <text x="248" y="128" font-size="10" fill="var(--accent)" font-family="var(--mono)" opacity="0.8">ρ₁</text>
          <text x="368" y="110" font-size="10" fill="var(--accent2)" font-family="var(--mono)" opacity="0.8">ρ₂</text>
          <text x="308" y="200" font-size="10" fill="#fbbf24" font-family="var(--mono)" opacity="0.8">ρ₃</text>
        </svg>
      </div>

      <p>
        Mathematically, each pseudorange defines a sphere equation. For satellite <em>i</em> at known
        position (x<sub>i</sub>, y<sub>i</sub>, z<sub>i</sub>), the pseudorange ρ<sub>i</sub> to receiver
        at unknown position (x, y, z) is:
      </p>

      <div class="formula-block">
        <div class="formula">ρ<sub>i</sub> = √[(x − x<sub>i</sub>)² + (y − y<sub>i</sub>)² + (z − z<sub>i</sub>)²] + c·δt</div>
        <div class="formula-desc">
          where <em>c·δt</em> is the receiver clock error term (clock offset in seconds × speed of light).
          The unknowns are x, y, z (position) and δt (receiver clock offset).
        </div>
      </div>

      <!-- SECTION 4 -->
      <h2 id="four-satellites">Why four satellites?</h2>
      <p>
        Three spheres give you a 3D position — so why do textbooks always say you need <em>four</em> satellites?
      </p>
      <p>
        Because of the receiver clock error <strong>δt</strong>. The receiver's internal clock is a cheap
        quartz oscillator, not an atomic clock. Its offset from true GNSS system time is unknown and must
        be solved for simultaneously. That adds a <strong>fourth unknown</strong> to the system.
      </p>
      <p>
        To solve for four unknowns (x, y, z, δt) you need at least four equations — one pseudorange per satellite.
        Four satellites give you exactly four equations, which can be solved (with some iteration) for the four unknowns.
      </p>

      <div class="unknowns-grid">
        <div class="unknown-card">
          <div class="unknown-symbol">x</div>
          <div class="unknown-label">East position</div>
        </div>
        <div class="unknown-card">
          <div class="unknown-symbol">y</div>
          <div class="unknown-label">North position</div>
        </div>
        <div class="unknown-card">
          <div class="unknown-symbol">z</div>
          <div class="unknown-label">Up position</div>
        </div>
        <div class="unknown-card unknown-clock">
          <div class="unknown-symbol">δt</div>
          <div class="unknown-label">Clock offset</div>
        </div>
      </div>

      <p>
        In practice, modern receivers track 10–40 satellites simultaneously. The overdetermined system
        (more equations than unknowns) is solved using least squares estimation, which improves accuracy
        and enables integrity checks. More satellites = better geometry = lower DOP = more accurate position.
      </p>

      <!-- SECTION 5 -->
      <h2 id="receiver">What the receiver actually does</h2>
      <p>
        A GNSS receiver performs several steps in a continuous loop:
      </p>

      <ol class="steps">
        <li>
          <strong>Signal acquisition</strong> — search for satellite signals by scanning frequencies and
          code phases. This is the slow part (cold start can take 30–60 seconds).
        </li>
        <li>
          <strong>Signal tracking</strong> — once acquired, a phase-locked loop (PLL) tracks the carrier
          phase and a delay-locked loop (DLL) tracks the code phase continuously.
        </li>
        <li>
          <strong>Navigation message decoding</strong> — extract satellite position (ephemeris) and clock
          correction parameters from the 50 bps navigation message broadcast by each satellite.
        </li>
        <li>
          <strong>Pseudorange measurement</strong> — measure the code phase offset between received and
          locally generated signal to compute the pseudorange.
        </li>
        <li>
          <strong>Position solution</strong> — using pseudoranges from ≥4 satellites and their known positions
          (from ephemeris), solve the nonlinear system of equations iteratively for (x, y, z, δt).
        </li>
        <li>
          <strong>Output</strong> — convert the 3D ECEF position to latitude, longitude and height.
          Format as NMEA sentences or proprietary binary and send to the host application.
        </li>
      </ol>

      <div class="callout callout-info">
        <div class="callout-icon">🔄</div>
        <div>
          <strong>Update rate:</strong> Consumer GNSS receivers typically output positions at 1 Hz (once per second).
          High-performance receivers can output at 10, 20, or even 100 Hz. The fundamental measurement loop
          runs faster still — typically at the chip rate of the ranging code (1.023 MHz for GPS C/A code).
        </div>
      </div>

      <!-- SECTION 6 - SUMMARY -->
      <h2 id="summary">Summary</h2>

      <div class="summary-grid">
        <div class="summary-card">
          <div class="summary-icon">📡</div>
          <div class="summary-title">Signal travel time</div>
          <div class="summary-body">Satellites broadcast timestamped signals. The receiver measures how long each signal took to arrive — this is the pseudorange.</div>
        </div>
        <div class="summary-card">
          <div class="summary-icon">🌐</div>
          <div class="summary-title">Trilateration</div>
          <div class="summary-body">Four or more pseudoranges define four or more spheres. The receiver is at their intersection — solving simultaneously for position and clock error.</div>
        </div>
        <div class="summary-card">
          <div class="summary-icon">⏱️</div>
          <div class="summary-title">The clock problem</div>
          <div class="summary-body">Receiver clocks are not precise enough — a 1 µs error means 300 m of ranging error. The receiver clock offset is solved as a fourth unknown alongside position.</div>
        </div>
        <div class="summary-card">
          <div class="summary-icon">📈</div>
          <div class="summary-title">More satellites = better</div>
          <div class="summary-body">With more than 4 satellites, the overdetermined system is solved by least squares. This improves accuracy, redundancy and enables error detection.</div>
        </div>
      </div>

      <!-- NEXT ARTICLE -->
      <div class="next-article">
        <div class="next-label">Next in Fundamentals</div>
        <a href="/learn/fundamentals/signals-and-frequencies" class="next-card">
          <div>
            <div class="next-title">GNSS Signals and Frequencies →</div>
            <div class="next-desc">L-band frequencies, signal structure, CDMA vs FDMA, spreading codes and carrier phase.</div>
          </div>
        </a>
      </div>

      <!-- REFERENCES -->
      <div class="references" id="references">
        <h3>References and further reading</h3>
        <ul>
          <li>
            Kaplan, E. D. & Hegarty, C. J. (2017). <em>Understanding GPS/GNSS: Principles and Applications</em>, 3rd ed. Artech House.
          </li>
          <li>
            IS-GPS-200N — Interface Specification for GPS.
            <a href="https://www.navcen.uscg.gov/sites/default/files/pdf/gps/IS-GPS-200N.pdf" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">NAVCEN →</a>
          </li>
          <li>
            Teunissen, P. J. G. & Montenbruck, O. (eds.) (2017). <em>Springer Handbook of Global Navigation Satellite Systems</em>. Springer.
          </li>
          <li>
            Misra, P. & Enge, P. (2011). <em>Global Positioning System: Signals, Measurements and Performance</em>, 2nd ed. Ganga-Jamuna Press.
          </li>
        </ul>
      </div>

    </div>
  </section>
</Layout>

<style>
  .learn-container { max-width: 820px; }

  /* Breadcrumb */
  .breadcrumb { display: flex; align-items: center; gap: 8px; font-size: 13px; color: var(--text3); margin-bottom: 28px; flex-wrap: wrap; }
  .breadcrumb a { color: var(--text2); transition: color 0.2s; }
  .breadcrumb a:hover { color: var(--accent); }
  .breadcrumb span { color: var(--text3); }

  /* Article header */
  .article-header { margin-bottom: 36px; }
  h1 { font-size: clamp(24px, 4vw, 38px); font-weight: 700; margin: 10px 0 16px; line-height: 1.2; }
  .lead { font-size: 17px; color: var(--text2); line-height: 1.8; margin-bottom: 12px; max-width: 720px; }
  .article-meta { font-size: 12px; color: var(--text3); font-family: var(--mono); display: flex; gap: 8px; }

  /* TOC */
  .toc { background: var(--bg2); border: 1px solid var(--border); border-radius: 10px; padding: 20px 24px; margin-bottom: 40px; }
  .toc-title { font-size: 11px; font-weight: 600; letter-spacing: 0.1em; text-transform: uppercase; color: var(--text3); font-family: var(--mono); margin-bottom: 10px; }
  .toc ol { margin: 0; padding-left: 18px; display: flex; flex-direction: column; gap: 6px; }
  .toc li { font-size: 14px; }
  .toc a { color: var(--text2); transition: color 0.2s; }
  .toc a:hover { color: var(--accent); }

  /* Body text */
  h2 { font-size: 22px; font-weight: 700; margin: 40px 0 16px; padding-top: 8px; border-top: 1px solid var(--border); }
  p { font-size: 15px; color: var(--text2); line-height: 1.8; margin-bottom: 16px; }
  ul, ol { font-size: 15px; color: var(--text2); line-height: 1.8; padding-left: 24px; margin-bottom: 16px; }
  li { margin-bottom: 6px; }
  strong { color: var(--text); font-weight: 600; }
  em { color: var(--text2); }
  sub { font-size: 0.75em; }

  /* Callouts */
  .callout { display: flex; gap: 14px; padding: 16px 20px; border-radius: 10px; margin: 24px 0; font-size: 14px; line-height: 1.7; }
  .callout-icon { font-size: 18px; flex-shrink: 0; padding-top: 1px; }
  .callout-info { background: rgba(0,153,255,0.06); border: 1px solid rgba(0,153,255,0.18); color: var(--text2); }
  .callout-warn { background: rgba(251,191,36,0.06); border: 1px solid rgba(251,191,36,0.2); color: var(--text2); }
  .callout strong { color: var(--text); }

  /* Formulas */
  .formula-block { background: var(--bg2); border: 1px solid var(--border); border-left: 3px solid var(--accent); border-radius: 8px; padding: 18px 20px; margin: 20px 0; }
  .formula { font-family: var(--mono); font-size: 16px; color: var(--text); margin-bottom: 8px; }
  .formula-desc { font-size: 13px; color: var(--text3); line-height: 1.6; }

  /* Diagrams */
  .diagram-wrap { background: var(--bg2); border: 1px solid var(--border); border-radius: 10px; padding: 20px; margin: 24px 0; }
  .diagram-label { font-size: 11px; color: var(--text3); font-family: var(--mono); text-transform: uppercase; letter-spacing: 0.08em; margin-bottom: 12px; }

  /* Unknowns grid */
  .unknowns-grid { display: grid; grid-template-columns: repeat(4, 1fr); gap: 12px; margin: 20px 0; }
  .unknown-card { background: var(--bg2); border: 1px solid var(--border); border-radius: 10px; padding: 16px; text-align: center; }
  .unknown-clock { border-color: rgba(0,212,170,0.3); background: rgba(0,212,170,0.04); }
  .unknown-symbol { font-size: 28px; font-weight: 700; font-family: var(--mono); color: var(--accent); margin-bottom: 6px; }
  .unknown-label { font-size: 12px; color: var(--text3); }

  /* Steps */
  .steps { counter-reset: step; list-style: none; padding: 0; }
  .steps li { counter-increment: step; padding: 14px 14px 14px 52px; position: relative; border-bottom: 1px solid var(--border); font-size: 15px; color: var(--text2); line-height: 1.7; }
  .steps li:last-child { border-bottom: none; }
  .steps li::before { content: counter(step); position: absolute; left: 12px; top: 14px; width: 24px; height: 24px; background: rgba(0,212,170,0.12); color: var(--accent); border-radius: 50%; font-size: 12px; font-weight: 600; display: flex; align-items: center; justify-content: center; font-family: var(--mono); }

  /* Summary grid */
  .summary-grid { display: grid; grid-template-columns: repeat(2, 1fr); gap: 14px; margin: 24px 0; }
  .summary-card { background: var(--bg2); border: 1px solid var(--border); border-radius: 10px; padding: 20px; }
  .summary-icon { font-size: 22px; margin-bottom: 10px; }
  .summary-title { font-size: 14px; font-weight: 600; color: var(--text); margin-bottom: 6px; }
  .summary-body { font-size: 13px; color: var(--text3); line-height: 1.6; }

  /* Next article */
  .next-article { margin: 48px 0 32px; }
  .next-label { font-size: 11px; color: var(--text3); font-family: var(--mono); text-transform: uppercase; letter-spacing: 0.08em; margin-bottom: 10px; }
  .next-card { display: block; background: var(--bg2); border: 1px solid var(--border); border-radius: 10px; padding: 20px 24px; transition: border-color 0.2s; }
  .next-card:hover { border-color: rgba(0,212,170,0.3); }
  .next-title { font-size: 16px; font-weight: 600; color: var(--accent); margin-bottom: 6px; }
  .next-desc { font-size: 13px; color: var(--text3); line-height: 1.5; }

  /* References */
  .references { border-top: 1px solid var(--border); padding-top: 28px; margin-top: 8px; }
  .references h3 { font-size: 14px; font-weight: 600; color: var(--text3); margin-bottom: 14px; text-transform: uppercase; letter-spacing: 0.06em; font-family: var(--mono); }
  .references ul { list-style: none; padding: 0; display: flex; flex-direction: column; gap: 10px; }
  .references li { font-size: 13px; color: var(--text3); line-height: 1.6; padding-left: 16px; border-left: 2px solid var(--border); }
  .references a { color: var(--accent2); text-decoration: underline; text-underline-offset: 2px; }

  /* Responsive */
  @media (max-width: 640px) {
    .unknowns-grid { grid-template-columns: repeat(2, 1fr); }
    .summary-grid { grid-template-columns: 1fr; }
    h2 { font-size: 20px; }
  }
</style>